{
  "doc_id": "51018",
  "text": "An auditory Stroop approach could be useful for clinical purposes. Abnormal conflict management was evidenced for several brain disorders, e.g., attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder [for review see [CITATION_1] or in paranoid schizophrenia [CITATION_2] ]. An auditory approach to the common Stroop interference task seems of particular interest since the auditory sense is especially affected in psychiatric disorders such as schizophrenia [CITATION_3] . Recently, it has been reported that an increased Stroop effect can serve as a marker for a genetic vulnerability to schizophrenia [e.g., [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Because schizophrenic patients have deficits in both auditory processing and conflict monitoring, an auditory version of the Stroop task might provide an even more sensitive trait marker for schizophrenia.",
